<Base
	title="Capabilities"
	description="Advisory in data and AI strategy, digital platforms and digital twins, and capital delivery transformation for infrastructure programmes."
>
	<div class="page-head">
		<h1 class="page-title">Capabilities</h1>
		<p class="lede">
			Three places where digital and data decide whether a capital programme
			lands. What you choose to build, what you build it on, and how the
			organisation around it works.
		</p>
	</div>

	<section class="capability reveal">
		<h2 class="capability-title tick">Data and AI strategy</h2>
		<p>
			Most organisations know they need data and AI. Fewer have decided what
			those tools are actually for, or who owns the decisions they are meant
			to improve. I help capital delivery organisations and asset owners
			build a data and AI strategy around the decisions it has to change, so
			it survives contact with a live programme rather than ending as a
			pilot. That means being clear about the questions the investment must
			answer, the standards that keep it trustworthy, and the ownership that
			keeps it working once the first team has moved on. I bring the
			engineering judgement to know which problems are worth solving with
			data, and the commercial discipline to put the case in terms a finance
			or investment committee will act on.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="capability reveal">
		<h2 class="capability-title tick">Digital platforms and digital twins</h2>
		<p>
			Platforms, digital twins and asset data are easy to specify and hard
			to keep. Too many are built for the people who commission them and
			abandoned by the people who inherit them at handover. I work on the
			ones meant to last, operable and owned once the programme that built
			them has gone. The data that lets a twin stay trustworthy in
			operation is usually fixed years earlier, when the contracts are
			written, not when the asset opens. So the test I apply is practical.
			What decision does this improve, who acts on it, and what has to be
			true at commissioning for it to still be working a year later. I keep
			the work tool-agnostic and anchored in the systems a client already
			runs, so it strengthens what they have rather than adding another
			platform to maintain.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="capability reveal">
		<h2 class="capability-title tick">Capital delivery transformation</h2>
		<p>
			Large programmes rarely fail for want of engineering. They fail at
			the seams, where agencies, partners and systems meet and no one owns
			the join. I help owners and delivery organisations design the
			operating model, governance and systems-engineering discipline that
			hold a multi-agency programme together, so decisions get made once,
			by the right people, with the evidence in front of them. I have done
			this on complex programmes in both the UK and the Gulf, aligning
			shared standards and clear decision rights so a programme moves as
			one body rather than a set of parts. The work carries through
			mobilisation and into early operations, with benefits measures that
			show whether the change actually took.
		</p>
	</section>
</Base>
